'''Austin Richard Post''' (born July 4, 1995),<ref name="Syr">{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Geoff |title=Rapper Post Malone's father talks Syracuse roots, musical influences—and haters |url=https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2017/10/post_malone_syracuse_father.html |publisher=syracuse.com |access-date=April 1, 2019 |date=October 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402044650/https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/2017/10/post_malone_syracuse_father.html |archive-date=April 2, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> known professionally as '''Post Malone''', is an American rapper, singer, songwriter, record producer, and guitarist.<ref>{{cite web |title=How Post Malone Became The Most Random Success In Rap |url=https://www.thefader.com/2015/05/14/everything-you-need-to-know-about-post-malone |access-date=2022-06-10 |website=The FADER |language=en |archive-date=June 10, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220610140904/https://www.thefader.com/2015/05/14/everything-you-need-to-know-about-post-malone |url-status=live }}</ref> He has gained distinction and acclaim for his blending of various genres including [[Hip hop music|hip hop]], [[Pop music|pop]], [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[Trap music|trap]], and [[Country music|country]]. His [[stage name]] was derived from inputting his birth name into a rap name generator.<ref name="vh1.com">{{cite web |url=https://www.vh1.com/news/xwrgfw/post-malone-explains-how-he-got-his-name-martha-and-snoop |title=Find Out How Post Malone Got His Name (and All of His Tattoos) in This Martha & Snoop Bonus Clip |last1=Wurzburger |first1=Andrea |website=VH1 News |access-date=November 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171121142207/http://www.vh1.com/news/333717/post-malone-explains-how-he-got-his-name-martha-and-snoop/|archive-date=November 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>

Malone began his musical career in 2011, and gained recognition with his 2015 debut single "[[White Iverson]]",<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://soundcloud.com/postmalone/white-iverson |title=White Iverson by Post Malone |access-date=October 3, 2015 |website=SoundCloud |publisher=Post Malone|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151005114933/https://soundcloud.com/postmalone/white-iverson|archive-date = October 5, 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> which peaked at number 14 on the U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. He signed with [[Republic Records]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malone-signs-with-republic-records-news.17053.html |title=Post Malone Signs With Republic Records |date=August 14, 2015 |access-date=October 3, 2015 |website=HotNewHipHop |last=Schwartz |first=Danny|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151004185327/http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malone-signs-with-republic-records-news.17053.html|archive-date = October 4, 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> to release his debut studio album ''[[Stoney (album)|Stoney]]'' (2016), which peaked at number four on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and spawned the [[RIAA certification|diamond]]-certified single "[[Congratulations (Post Malone song)|Congratulations]]" (featuring [[Quavo]]).<ref name=":7" /> His second album, ''[[Beerbongs & Bentleys]]'' (2018) debuted atop the ''Billboard'' 200 and set numerous [[Streaming media|streaming]] records.<ref name=":7">{{Cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/post-malone-broke-a-34-year-michael-jackson-record-how-705514/ |title=Post Malone Broke a 34-Year-Old Michael Jackson Record. How? |last=Wang |first=Amy X. |date=August 18, 2018 |magazine=Rolling Stone|access-date=August 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180819113158/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/post-malone-broke-a-34-year-michael-jackson-record-how-705514/|archive-date=August 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> It contained the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 number-one singles "[[Rockstar (Post Malone song)|Rockstar]]" (featuring [[21 Savage]]) and "[[Psycho (Post Malone song)|Psycho]]" (featuring [[Ty Dolla Sign]]), and was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] at the [[61st Annual Grammy Awards|61st Grammy Awards]]. His third ''Billboard'' Hot 100-number one single, "[[Sunflower (Post Malone and Swae Lee song)|Sunflower]]" (with [[Swae Lee]]), was released for [[Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse (soundtrack)|the accompanying soundtrack]] to the 2018 animated film ''[[Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse]]''; it became the highest-certified song in [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]] history as the first to receive [[RIAA certification|double diamond]] (20-times platinum) certification.

"Sunflower" was also included on Malone's third album, ''[[Hollywood's Bleeding]]'' (2019), which became his second to peak atop the ''Billboard'' 200 and received his second nomination for Album of the Year at the [[63rd Annual Grammy Awards|63rd Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/post-malone-and-swae-lee-make-history-with-first-ever-riaa-double-diamond-single-sunflower-spider-man-into-the-spider-verse/ |title=Post Malone and Swae Lee Make History with First-Ever RIAA Double-Diamond Single "SUNFLOWER (SPIDER-MAN: INTO THE SPIDER-VERSE)" |website=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] |date=February 8, 2024 |access-date=2024-02-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Gold & Platinum |url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/ |access-date=2023-05-11 |website=RIAA |language=en-US}}</ref> It spawned the single "[[Circles (Post Malone song)|Circles]]", which became his fourth number-one song on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, and spent 61 weeks on the chart.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2020/radio-songs|title = Radio Songs|magazine = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date = January 2, 2013}}</ref>
His fourth and fifth albums, ''[[Twelve Carat Toothache]]'' (2022) and [[Austin (album)|''Austin'']] (2023), both peaked at number two on the ''Billboard'' 200 and saw continued success; the former spawned the top ten singles "[[I Like You (A Happier Song)]]" (featuring [[Doja Cat]]) and "[[One Right Now]]" (with [[the Weeknd]]), while the latter explored [[pop rock]] and spawned the top 20 single, "[[Chemical (Post Malone song)|Chemical]]". Two of his 2024 singles debuted atop the ''Billboard'' Hot 100: his guest appearance on [[Taylor Swift]]'s "[[Fortnight (song)|Fortnight]]", and his first [[country pop]] song, "[[I Had Some Help]]" (featuring [[Morgan Wallen]]). The latter served as lead single for his sixth album, ''[[F-1 Trillion]]'' (2024), which further experimented with the genre and became his third non-consecutive number one album on the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2024/05/09/post-malones-journey-into-country-music-continues-with-another-hit/?sh=551a20c32883|title=Post Malone's Journey Into Country Music Continues With Another Hit|date=May 9, 2024|website=Forbes.com}}</ref>

Malone is among the [[List of best-selling music artists|best-selling music artists]], with over 80 million records sold.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Mendoza |first=Diego |date=2022-05-06 |title='I'm the happiest I've ever been': Post Malone announces girlfriend's pregnancy |url=https://www.khou.com/article/news/entertainment-news/post-malone-expecting-first-child/507-698d7d27-21b2-4672-85e7-155e8080e6d9 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220818012213/https://www.khou.com/article/news/entertainment-news/post-malone-expecting-first-child/507-698d7d27-21b2-4672-85e7-155e8080e6d9 |archive-date=2022-08-18 |access-date=2022-08-17 |website=khou.com |language=en-US}}</ref> His [[List of awards and nominations received by Post Malone|accolades]] include ten [[Billboard Music Award|''Billboard'' Music Awards]], three [[American Music Awards]], one [[MTV Video Music Awards|MTV Video Music Award]], and nine [[Grammy Award]] nominations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/post-malone |title=Post Malone |date=May 12, 2018 |website=GRAMMY.com|access-date=June 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190208112544/https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/post-malone|archive-date=February 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He holds several ''Billboard'' chart records: He is the first solo lead artist to top both the [[Rap Airplay]] and [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] charts, while "Circles" set the record for longest climb to number one (41 weeks) on the Adult Contemporary chart by a solo artist.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9430625/post-malone-circles-tops-ac-chart |title=Post Malone's 'Circles' Sets More Records With Run to No. 1 on Adult Contemporary Chart |access-date=August 10, 2020 |magazine=Billboard |last=Trust |first=Gary |url-status=live |archive-date=August 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200810003325/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9430625/post-malone-circles-tops-ac-chart }}</ref> As of {{currentyear}}, Malone holds the record for the artist with the most diamond-certified songs, with nine to his name.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ahlgrim |first1=Callie |title=Only 23 artists have multiple songs that are certified diamond — here they all are |url=https://www.insider.com/artists-singers-with-multiple-diamond-certified-songs-riaa-2022-7 |website=insider.com |access-date=21 September 2023}}</ref>

==Early life==
Austin Richard Post was born on July 4, 1995,<ref name=Syr /> in [[Syracuse, New York]].<ref name=":5">{{cite web |url=http://pigeonsandplanes.com/2015/06/post-malone-homecoming/ |title=Post Malone's Homecoming |date=June 23, 2015 |access-date=October 17, 2015 |website=Pigeons & Planes |last=Blackburn |first=H. Drew|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151026191908/http://pigeonsandplanes.com/2015/06/post-malone-homecoming/|archive-date=October 26, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/postmalone/status/635996834859581440 |title=Post Malone on Twitter: "I've never been anyone except for Austin Richard Post. i ain't never fold/break." |publisher=Twitter |access-date=May 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170121170809/https://twitter.com/postmalone/status/635996834859581440|archive-date=January 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He was raised by his father, Richard Post, and his stepmother, Jodie. His father had been a [[Disc jockey|DJ]] in his youth and introduced Malone to many different genres of music including [[Hip hop music|hip hop]], [[Country music|country]], and [[Rock music|rock]].<ref name="syracuse">{{Cite news |url=http://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2017/10/post_malone_syracuse_father.html |title=Rapper Post Malone's father talks Syracuse roots, musical influences – and haters |work=syracuse.com|access-date=December 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201081403/http://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2017/10/post_malone_syracuse_father.html|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> When Malone was nine years old,<ref>{{cite podcast |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l65hR94nfqY&t=11m48s |date=May 22, 2017 |access-date=August 11, 2017 |title=H3 Podcast #7 – Post Malone & Joji |time=11:48 |host=[[h3h3Productions]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626224331/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l65hR94nfqY&t=11m48s |archive-date=June 26, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> he and his family moved to [[Grapevine, Texas]], after his father became the manager of [[concession stand|concessions]] for the [[Dallas Cowboys]] football team.<ref name="papermag">{{cite news |last1=Valentine |first1=Claire |title=Post Malone on Memes, Bieber Fans, and the Importance of Beer |url=http://www.papermag.com/riding-with-post-malone-3-2493835927.html |website=PAPER |access-date=November 19, 2017 |date=October 6, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171119003943/http://www.papermag.com/riding-with-post-malone-3-2493835927.html|archive-date=November 19, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{cite web |url=http://www.slamonline.com/the-magazine/features/white-iverson-post-malone-interview/ |title=The New 3 |date=April 30, 2015 |access-date=October 3, 2015 |website=SLAMonline |last=Figman |first=Adam|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151002212937/http://www.slamonline.com/the-magazine/features/white-iverson-post-malone-interview/|archive-date=October 2, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Malone began to play the guitar and auditioned for the American band [[Crown the Empire]] in 2010, but was rejected after his guitar strings broke during the audition. He credited his initial interest in learning guitar to the video game ''[[Guitar Hero]]''.<ref name="rollingstone" />

Malone has expressed his affinity for [[alternative rock]] music, and appeared for a DJ set at Emo Nite in [[Los Angeles]], California, in June 2017, playing songs by American alt-rock band [[My Chemical Romance]] at the event.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VzJa8Eql6A8 |title=Post Malone plays My Chemical Romance at Emo Nite |last=Emo Nite |date=June 8, 2017 |via=YouTube|access-date=June 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190104231720/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VzJa8Eql6A8|archive-date=January 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Malone, his first foray into professional music began when he was in a [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w-34Bnpbzkg?t=144 |title=GGN Post Malone Has The Sauce |last=westfesttv |date=February 9, 2016 |access-date=December 20, 2017 |via=YouTube |archive-date=August 28, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210828051314/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w-34Bnpbzkg%3Ft%3D144 |url-status=live }}</ref> He says soon afterwards he transitioned to softer rock as well as hip hop, before beginning to experiment on [[FL Studio]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w-34Bnpbzkg?t=164 |title=GGN Post Malone Has The Sauce |last=westfesttv |date=February 9, 2016 |access-date=December 20, 2017 |via=YouTube |archive-date=August 28, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210828051406/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w-34Bnpbzkg%3Ft%3D164 |url-status=live }}</ref>

==Career==
===2011–2016: Career beginnings and ''Stoney''===
{{Main|Stoney (album)|}}
[[File:Postmalone-ritual-may7-DREWYORKE-56 (17275323379).jpg|thumb|Malone performing in 2015|upright|left]]
According to Malone, he chose "Post Malone" as his [[stage name]] when he was "14 or 15".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=J2sO5AKGfKo?t=1882 |title=Post Malone – Stone Cold Podcast |last=Scare Wolf |date=August 15, 2017 |via=YouTube |access-date=December 20, 2017 |archive-date=March 5, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210305201611/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J2sO5AKGfKo%3Ft%3D1882 |url-status=live }}</ref> The name was rumored to be a reference to the professional basketball player [[Karl Malone]],<ref name=":4" /> but Malone later explained that "Post" is his last name, and he used a "rap name generator" to get "Malone".<ref name="vh1.com"/> At the age of 16, using audio editor [[Audacity (audio editor)|Audacity]], Malone created his first [[mixtape]], ''Young and After Them Riches''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w-34Bnpbzkg?t=268 |title=GGN Post Malone Has The Sauce |last=westfesttv |date=February 9, 2016 |via=YouTube |access-date=December 20, 2017 |archive-date=May 9, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210509064339/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w-34Bnpbzkg%3Ft%3D268 |url-status=live }}</ref> He showed it to some of his classmates at [[Grapevine High School]].<ref name="rollingstone" /><ref name=":2">{{cite web |url=http://www.thefader.com/2015/05/14/everything-you-need-to-know-about-post-malone |title=How Post Malone Became The Most Random Success In Rap |last=Golden |first=Zara |date=May 14, 2015 |website=The FADER |access-date=October 3, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926073108/http://www.thefader.com/2015/05/14/everything-you-need-to-know-about-post-malone|archive-date=September 26, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> He was voted "Most Likely to Become Famous" by his classmates as a senior in high school. He worked at a [[Chicken Express]] as a teenager.<ref name="rollingstone" />

At age 17, Malone released a parody [[synth-pop]] [[sentimental ballad|ballad]] song called "Why Don't You Love Me" under the alias Leon DeChino, intended for a school project. The song reappeared online in 2016. Malone later referenced the DeChino alias on his song "Psycho".<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Morel Jr. |first1=Jacques |last2=Hill |first2=Tia |author3=Oppi |last4=Brown |first4=Lisa |date=April 4, 2018 |title=The Story Behind Post Malone's Alter Ego Leon DeChino |work=[[Genius (company)|Genius]] |url=https://genius.com/a/the-story-behind-post-malone-s-alter-ego-leon-dechino |access-date=July 23, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Kelly |first=Chris |date=February 7, 2016 |title=Post Malone's underage, suburban crowd was a perfect match for him |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/music/post-malones-underage-suburban-crowd-was-a-perfect-match-for-him/2016/02/07/cecdb71c-ccfe-11e5-b9ab-26591104bb19_story.html |access-date=July 23, 2023}}</ref>

Malone later enrolled in [[Tarrant County College]], but dropped out.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VP_ki-W3cLY&t=8m42s |title=Post Malone Goes Undercover on Twitter, Facebook, Quora, and Reddit |date=December 21, 2017 |work=[[GQ]] |via=[[YouTube]] |access-date=December 21, 2017 |quote=I didn't go to Syracuse ... I went to Tarrant County College |archive-date=August 28, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210828051406/https://accounts.google.com/ServiceLogin?service=youtube&uilel=3&passive=true&continue=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fsignin%3Faction_handle_signin%3Dtrue%26app%3Ddesktop%26hl%3Den%26next%3D%252Fsignin_passive%26feature%3Dpassive&hl=en |url-status=live }}</ref> After leaving college, Malone moved to Los Angeles with his longtime friend Jason Probst, a professional game streamer.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sxQ-pxzzSqg |title=Nardwuar vs. Post Malone |date=December 10, 2017 |via=YouTube |access-date=December 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213224959/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sxQ-pxzzSqg|archive-date=December 13, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s4XLaXoUdX4 |title='Post Malone' exposed part of minecraft (Before He Was Famous) |date=December 21, 2016 |via=YouTube |access-date=December 13, 2017 |archive-date=August 28, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210828051420/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s4XLaXoUdX4 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w-34Bnpbzkg?t=383 |title=GGN Post Malone Has The Sauce |date=February 9, 2016 |via=YouTube |access-date=December 13, 2017 |archive-date=August 28, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210828051335/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w-34Bnpbzkg%3Ft%3D383 |url-status=live }}</ref>

After moving to Los Angeles, Malone, Probst, and several other producers and artists formed the music group BLCKVRD and recorded music together.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2016/05/post-malone-white-iverson-profile |title=How Post Malone Went From SoundCloud to Stadium Status |website=Complex |access-date=December 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171216053121/http://www.complex.com/music/2016/05/post-malone-white-iverson-profile|archive-date=December 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Several members of the group, including Malone, moved into a house in the [[San Fernando Valley]] together. While living in the San Fernando Valley, Malone met record producers [[FKi 1st]] and Sauce Lord Rich, who formed the production team [[FKi (production team)|FKi]], as well as Rex Kudo, who produced several of Malone's tracks, including "[[White Iverson]]".<ref name=":5" /> Malone recorded the song two days after writing it.<ref name=":2" /> The lyrics of "White Iverson" allude to [[Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame|Basketball Hall of Fame]] player [[Allen Iverson]].<ref name=":1">{{cite web |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TkNOkxwM9DY |title=Post Malone at The Breakfast Club: Talks White Iverson, Is He A Culture Vulture & More (August 24, 2015) |date=August 24, 2015 |access-date=October 3, 2015 |via=[[YouTube]] |publisher=TheBreakFastClub|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151030121228/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TkNOkxwM9DY|archive-date=October 30, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":3">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/6671466/post-malone/biography |title=Post Malone – Biography |access-date=October 3, 2015 |magazine=Billboard |last=Jeffries |first=David|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912195143/http://www.billboard.com/artist/6671466/post-malone/biography|archive-date=September 12, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":4">{{cite web |date=July 18, 2015 |access-date=October 3, 2015 |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2217693/post-malone-white-iverson-video/ |title=Video Premiere: Watch Post Malone's 'White Iverson' |publisher=MTV |last=Markman |first=Rob|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151005051932/http://www.mtv.com/news/2217693/post-malone-white-iverson-video/|archive-date=October 5, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> In February 2015, upon completion, it was uploaded to Malone's SoundCloud account.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://soundcloud.com/postmalone/white-iverson |title=White Iverson by Post Malone |access-date=October 3, 2015 |website=[[SoundCloud]] |publisher=Post Malone|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151005114933/https://soundcloud.com/postmalone/white-iverson|archive-date=October 5, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> On July 19, 2015, Malone released a music video for "White Iverson". The single received praise from [[Mac Miller]] and [[Wiz Khalifa]].<ref name="rollingstone" /><ref name="success">{{cite web |last1=Payne |first1=Ogden |title=Inside The Hidden Success Of Post Malone |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ogdenpayne/2017/02/03/inside-the-hidden-success-of-post-malone/ |website=Forbes |access-date=November 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201044626/https://www.forbes.com/sites/ogdenpayne/2017/02/03/inside-the-hidden-success-of-post-malone/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Mac |title=Mac Miller tweet |url=https://twitter.com/macmiller/status/563437879427211264 |website=Twitter |access-date=November 20, 2017}}</ref> However the song was mocked by [[Earl Sweatshirt]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Walsh |first1=Peter |title=Earl Sweatshirt Isn't a Fan of Post Malone |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/01/earl-sweatshirt-isnt-a-fan-of-white-iverson-post-malone-responds/ |website=XXL Mag |date=January 28, 2016 |access-date=November 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171116214423/http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/01/earl-sweatshirt-isnt-a-fan-of-white-iverson-post-malone-responds|archive-date=November 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Brandle |first1=Lars |title=Earl Sweatshirt Criticizes Post Malone's 'White Iverson,' Malone Responds |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6858390/earl-sweatshirt-criticizes-post-malone-white-iverson |magazine=Billboard |access-date=November 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928052259/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6858390/earl-sweatshirt-criticizes-post-malone-white-iverson|archive-date=September 28, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mench |first1=Chris |title=Earl Sweatshirt Finally Heard Post Malone's "White Iverson" and He Doesn't Seem to Be a Fan |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2016/01/earl-sweatshirt-finally-heard-post-malone-white-iverson-doesnt-seem-to-be-fan |website=Complex |access-date=November 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171123072510/http://www.complex.com/music/2016/01/earl-sweatshirt-finally-heard-post-malone-white-iverson-doesnt-seem-to-be-fan|archive-date=November 23, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:Post Malone (28150750483).jpg|thumb|upright|Malone at the [[VELD Music Festival]] in Canada in 2016]]

After hitting one million views within a month of releasing "White Iverson", Malone quickly garnered attention from record labels.<ref name=":3" /> In August 2015, he signed a [[recording contract]] with [[Republic Records]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malone-signs-with-republic-records-news.17053.html |title=Post Malone Signs With Republic Records |date=August 14, 2015 |access-date=October 3, 2015 |website=HotNewHipHop |last=Schwartz |first=Danny|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004185327/http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malone-signs-with-republic-records-news.17053.html|archive-date=October 4, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/garysuarez/2015/10/06/post-malone-white-iverson/ |title=Post Malone Scores With 'White Iverson' |last=Suarez |first=Gary |website=Forbes|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430071958/http://www.forbes.com/sites/garysuarez/2015/10/06/post-malone-white-iverson/|archive-date=April 30, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Malone went on to work with a number of prominent rappers including [[50 Cent]], [[Young Thug]], [[Kanye West]] and others.<ref>{{cite web |last=Akubuilo |first=Nneoma |date=February 12, 2016 |url=http://smashd.co/yeezy-season-3/ |title=Yeezy Season 3 |access-date=February 18, 2016|url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160301123451/http://smashd.co/yeezy-season-3/ |archive-date=March 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/magazine-feature/6762300/interview-post-malone-kanye-west |title=Rapper Post Malone on Collaborating With Kanye West: 'It Was the Scariest Experience Ever' |magazine=Billboard|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316142020/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/magazine-feature/6762300/interview-post-malone-kanye-west|archive-date=March 16, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In August 2015, he performed at [[Kylie Jenner]]'s 18th birthday party,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Yuscavage |first1=Chris |title=Here's James Harden Helping Post Malone Perform "White Iverson" at Kylie Jenner's 18th Birthday Party |url=http://www.complex.com/sports/2015/08/james-harden-helping-post-malone-perform-white-iverson-kylie-jenner-18th-birthday-party |website=Complex|access-date=November 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201035010/http://www.complex.com/sports/2015/08/james-harden-helping-post-malone-perform-white-iverson-kylie-jenner-18th-birthday-party|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> where he met Kanye West, who enjoyed his music, leading to him collaborating with Malone on his single "[[Fade (Kanye West song)|Fade]]" from his album ''[[The Life of Pablo]]'' (2016).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fleischer |first1=Adam |title=Without Kylie Jenner, This Buzzing Rapper Never Would Have Collaborated With Kanye West |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2350676/post-malone-kanye-west-i-feel-it-kylie-jenner/ |publisher=MTV News |access-date=November 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201064250/http://www.mtv.com/news/2350676/post-malone-kanye-west-i-feel-it-kylie-jenner/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Malone later began a friendship with Canadian singer [[Justin Bieber]] leading to Malone being an [[opening act]] for Bieber's [[Purpose World Tour]] (2016–17).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.freep.com/picture-gallery/entertainment/music/2016/04/25/justin-bieber-at-the-palace/83530406/ |title=Justin Bieber at the Palace |website=Detroit Free Press|access-date=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505040708/http://www.freep.com/picture-gallery/entertainment/music/2016/04/25/justin-bieber-at-the-palace/83530406/|archive-date=May 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-post-malone-20161216-story.html |title=Why Post Malone has been called 'the Donald Trump of hip-hop' |date=December 16, 2016 |access-date=December 19, 2016 |work=Los Angeles Times |last=Wood |first=Mikael | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161218211316/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-post-malone-20161216-story.html | archive-date = December 18, 2016 | url-status = live}}</ref> On April 20, 2016, Malone premiered his new single, "[[Go Flex]]" on [[Zane Lowe]]'s Beats 1 show.<ref>Simmons, Ted (April 21, 2016) [http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/new-music/2016/04/post-malone-go-flex-single/ Post Malone's New "Go Flex" Single Sounds Like Another Hit] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423224424/http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/new-music/2016/04/post-malone-go-flex-single/ |date=April 23, 2016 }}. xxlmag.com</ref>

On May 12, 2016, he released his first full-length project, a [[mixtape]], titled ''[[August 26th (mixtape)|August 26th]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malones-august-26-reportedly-dropping-today-at-noon-news.21580.html |title=Post Malone's "August 26" Reportedly Dropping Today At Noon' |last=Walker |first=Angus |website=HotNewHipHop|date=May 12, 2016 |access-date=May 12, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160512115851/http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malones-august-26-reportedly-dropping-today-at-noon-news.21580.html|archive-date=May 12, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> the title of which was a reference to the release date of his debut album. On June 9, 2016, Malone made his national television debut on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'', performing "Go Flex".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rap-up.com/2016/06/09/post-malone-performs-go-flex-on-jimmy-kimmel-live/ |title=Post Malone Performs 'Go Flex' on 'Jimmy Kimmel Live!' |access-date=July 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160713122429/http://www.rap-up.com/2016/06/09/post-malone-performs-go-flex-on-jimmy-kimmel-live/|archive-date=July 13, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>

In June 2016, [[XXL (magazine)|''XXL'']] editor-in-chief Vanessa Satten revealed Malone was considered for ''XXL''{{'}}s "2016 Freshman Class" magazine cover, but she was "told by his camp that he wasn't paying attention to hip hop so much. He was going in more of a [[Rock music|rock]]/[[Pop music|pop]]/[[Country music|country]] direction."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malone-going-in-rock-pop-country-direction-news.22223.html |title=Post Malone Going In "Rock/Pop/Country Direction" |website=HNHH |date=June 13, 2016 |access-date=July 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616140744/http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malone-going-in-rock-pop-country-direction-news.22223.html|archive-date=June 16, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> However, Malone denied these claims, explaining that his latest mixtape as well as his upcoming album were both hip hop.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BGtIKa7wYdo/ |title=Instagram post by Posty • Jun 16, 2016 at 6:21am UTC |website=Instagram|access-date=August 26, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170514004644/https://www.instagram.com/p/BGtIKa7wYdo/|archive-date=May 14, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In August 2016, Malone issued an apology for his album, ''[[Stoney (album)|Stoney]]'', being late.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Trevor |title=Post Malone Apologizes For Delay Of His Debut Album "Stoney" |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malone-apologizes-for-delay-of-his-debut-album-stoney-news.23749.html |website=Hot New Hip-Hop|date=August 28, 2016 |access-date=August 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829122659/http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malone-apologizes-for-delay-of-his-debut-album-stoney-news.23749.html|archive-date=August 29, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> It was available for pre-order on November 4, and was finally released on December 9. Malone later went on to call the album "mediocre",<ref name="papermag" /> despite the success of the single "Congratulations" (featuring [[Quavo]]), Malone's first top-ten song on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], peaking at number eight.<ref>{{cite web |last1=India |first1=Lindsey |title=Post Malone Earns First Top 10 Hit on Billboard Hot 100 Chart – XXL |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/06/post-malone-first-top-10-billboard-hot-100-chart/ |website=XXL Mag |date=June 7, 2017 |access-date=November 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201033618/http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/06/post-malone-first-top-10-billboard-hot-100-chart/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Morris |first1=Jessie |title=Post Malone Grabs Quavo for "Congratulations" |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2016/11/post-malone-new-song-congratulations-feat-quavo |website=Complex |access-date=November 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180118011219/http://www.complex.com/music/2016/11/post-malone-new-song-congratulations-feat-quavo|archive-date=January 18, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Stoney'' also featured the top 100 hits "[[I Fall Apart]]", and "[[Deja Vu (Post Malone song)|Deja Vu]]" (featuring Bieber), with the album later being certified double platinum by the [[RIAA]] in October 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gold & Platinum – RIAA |url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=POST+MALONE&ti=STONEY |website=RIAA |access-date=November 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626224336/https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=POST+MALONE&ti=STONEY|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

===2017–2019: ''Beerbongs & Bentleys'' and ''Hollywood's Bleeding''===
{{Main|Beerbongs & Bentleys|Hollywood's Bleeding}}

In February 2017, Malone revealed the title of his next project, ''[[Beerbongs & Bentleys]]'',<ref>Simmons, Ted (February 7, 2017) [http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/02/post-malone-stoney-gold/ Post Malone's 'Stoney' Album Goes Gold] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213164800/http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/02/post-malone-stoney-gold/ |date=February 13, 2017 }}. xxlmag.com</ref> and was set to be released in December, before eventually being pushed back to 2018.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Lamarre |first1=Carl |title=Post Malone Shares Release Date for 'Beerbongs & Bentleys' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8039646/post-malone-beerbongs-and-bentleys-release-date |magazine=Billboard |access-date=November 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180131185426/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8039646/post-malone-beerbongs-and-bentleys-release-date|archive-date=January 31, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In September, Malone released the first single from the album, "[[Rockstar (Post Malone song)|Rockstar]]" (featuring [[21 Savage]]). The song peaked at number one on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and held the spot for eight consecutive weeks<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8055045/hot-100-post-malone-rockstar-ed-sheeran-g-eazy |title=Post Malone's 'Rockstar' Leads Billboard Hot 100 for Eighth Week, G-Eazy's 'No Limit' Lifts to Top 10 |magazine=Billboard |first=Gary |last=Trust |date=December 4, 2017 |access-date=December 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205004855/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8055045/hot-100-post-malone-rockstar-ed-sheeran-g-eazy|archive-date=December 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> prompting ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' in 2017 to say he is "one of the most popular musicians in the country". In November of the same year, Malone released the official music video for "Rockstar", directed by [[Emil Nava]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Brandle |first1=Lars |title=Post Malone's New 'Rockstar' Music Video is Ultraviolent: Watch |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8046244/post-malone-rockstar-music-video-ultraviolent |magazine=Billboard |access-date=November 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171123022800/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8046244/post-malone-rockstar-music-video-ultraviolent|archive-date=November 23, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Orcutt |first1=KC |title=Post Malone and 21 Savage Drop Bloody ''Rockstar'' Video – XXL |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/11/post-malone-21-savage-rockstar-video/ |website=XXL Mag |date=November 22, 2017 |access-date=November 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122204248/http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/11/post-malone-21-savage-rockstar-video/|archive-date=November 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Renshaw |first1=David |title=Post Malone and 21 Savage star in the blood-soaked "rockstar" video |url=https://www.thefader.com/2017/11/22/post-malone-and-21-savage-star-in-the-blood-soaked-rockstar-video |website=The FADER |access-date=November 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171125031414/http://www.thefader.com/2017/11/22/post-malone-and-21-savage-star-in-the-blood-soaked-rockstar-video|archive-date=November 25, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Minsker |first1=Evan |title=Post Malone and 21 Savage Drop Ultra-Bloody New "rockstar" Video: Watch |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/post-malone-and-21-savage-get-super-bloody-in-new-rockstar-video-watch/ |website=Pitchfork |date=November 22, 2017 |access-date=November 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201043401/https://pitchfork.com/news/post-malone-and-21-savage-get-super-bloody-in-new-rockstar-video-watch/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>

On February 20, 2018, Malone previewed his new song with [[Ty Dolla Sign]] titled "[[Psycho (Post Malone song)|Psycho]]".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://pigeonsandplanes.com/news/2018/02/post-malone-ty-dolla-sign-psycho |title=Here's a Preview of Post Malone's New Single With Ty Dolla Sign "Psycho" |work=PigeonsandPlanes|access-date=March 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301104537/http://pigeonsandplanes.com/news/2018/02/post-malone-ty-dolla-sign-psycho|archive-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> "Psycho" was released on February 23, 2018,<ref>{{Citation |title=Psycho (feat. Ty Dolla $ign) – Single by Post Malone on Apple Music |date=February 23, 2018 |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/psycho-feat-ty-dolla-$ign-single/1349454257 |access-date=March 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301224824/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/psycho-feat-ty-dolla-$ign-single/1349454257|archive-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and a tour with 21 Savage was announced.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/02/post-malone-tour-21-savage-sob-x-rbe/ |title=Post Malone Is Going on Tour With 21 Savage and SOB x RBE – XXL |website=XXL Mag|date=February 20, 2018 |access-date=March 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301104138/http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/02/post-malone-tour-21-savage-sob-x-rbe/|archive-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The song debuted at number 2 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, becoming Malone's third entry in the top 10; it would later top the charts in June of that year, becoming Malone's second number one.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8231969/drake-gods-plan-post-malone-psycho-hot-100 |title=Drake's 'God's Plan' No. 1 on Billboard Hot 100 for Sixth Week, Post Malone's 'Psycho' Debuts at No. 2 |magazine=Billboard|access-date=March 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306062515/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8231969/drake-gods-plan-post-malone-psycho-hot-100|archive-date=March 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On April 5, 2018, Malone stated that ''Beerbongs & Bentleys'' will be released on April 27, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2018/04/post-malone-reveals-release-date-for-beerbongs-and-bentleys-and-previews-new-song |title=Post Malone Reveals Release Date for 'Beerbongs & Bentleys' and Previews New Song |work=Complex |last=Grant |first=Jasmine |date=April 5, 2018 |access-date=April 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180405083156/http://www.complex.com/music/2018/04/post-malone-reveals-release-date-for-beerbongs-and-bentleys-and-previews-new-song|archive-date=April 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day, he also premiered the song "Stay" during the Bud Lite Dive Bar show in Nashville.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/first-listen-preview-post-malones-brand-new-song-stay-194603814.html |title=Preview Post Malone's new song, 'Stay' |publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]] |last=Parker |first=Lyndsey |date=April 5, 2018 |access-date=April 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180404222821/https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/first-listen-preview-post-malones-brand-new-song-stay-194603814.html|archive-date=April 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Upon release, ''Beerbongs & Bentleys'' broke the first day streaming records on [[Spotify]], with 78.7&nbsp;million streams worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theindustryobserver.com.au/post-malones-beerbongs-bentleys/ |title=Post Malone's 'beerbongs & bentleys' smokes Spotify records |date=April 30, 2018 |last=Brandle |first=Lars |access-date=May 2, 2018 |work=The Industry Observer|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115021116/https://www.theindustryobserver.com.au/post-malones-beerbongs-bentleys/|archive-date=November 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> It debuted at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200 moving 461,000 [[album-equivalent unit]]s in its first week, with 153,000 coming from pure sales. The album was also certified platinum by the RIAA after four days<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2018/04/30/post-malones-new-album-has-been-certified-platinum-just-4-days-after-being-released/ |title=Post Malone's New Album Has Been Certified Platinum Just 4 Days After Being Released |date=April 30, 2018 |last=McIntyre |first=Hugh |access-date=May 2, 2018 |work=[[Forbes]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180502010954/https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2018/04/30/post-malones-new-album-has-been-certified-platinum-just-4-days-after-being-released/|archive-date=May 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and spawned three top 10 songs and six top 20 songs.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/post-malone/chart-history/hsi/ |title=Post Malone Chart History |magazine=Billboard|access-date=June 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507083802/https://www.billboard.com/music/Post-Malone/chart-history/hot-100|archive-date=May 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:Post Malone Stavernfestivalen 2018 (202128).jpg|thumb|Malone performing on the main stage at [[Stavernfestivalen]] in [[Stavern]], Norway in 2018]]

In an interview with ''Billboard'' in May 2018, Malone's manager announced that Malone was planning to start his own record label and film production company<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2018/05/post-malone-establish-record-label/ |title=Post Malone to establish his own record label |date=May 23, 2018 |work=Dancing Astronaut|access-date=May 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523204426/https://dancingastronaut.com/2018/05/post-malone-establish-record-label/|archive-date=May 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and Malone later won Top Rap Song at the ''Billboard'' Music Awards for "Rockstar".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malone-and-21-savages-rockstar-wins-top-rap-song-at-bbmas-news.50625.html |title=Post Malone & 21 Savage's "Rockstar" Wins Top Rap Song at BBMAs |work=HotNewHipHop|access-date=June 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612162201/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malone-and-21-savages-rockstar-wins-top-rap-song-at-bbmas-news.50625.html|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Malone confirmed in June 2018 that he was writing his third album,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8459421/post-malone-tweets-new-album-eminem |title=Post Malone Confirms He's Already Working on New Album, Shows Love For Eminem on Twitter |magazine=Billboard|access-date=June 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180606111819/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8459421/post-malone-tweets-new-album-eminem|archive-date=June 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and confirmed that a festival would be taking place, organized by him, titled "Posty Fest", in Dallas, Texas on October 28. Malone promised a "blockbuster" lineup with headliners like rapper [[Travis Scott]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/08/18/a-posthumous-lil-peep-and-xxxtentacion-collaboration-is-in-the-works |title=A posthumous Lil Peep and XXXTentacion collaboration is in the works |work=The FADER|access-date=August 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180819182134/https://www.thefader.com/2018/08/18/a-posthumous-lil-peep-and-xxxtentacion-collaboration-is-in-the-works|archive-date=August 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

In August, Malone broke [[Michael Jackson]]'s 34-year-old record for most weeks on ''Billboard''{{'}}s Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums chart, with ''Stoney'' reaching its 77th week on the ranking compared to the 76 weeks that ''[[Thriller (Michael Jackson album)|Thriller]]'' (1983) spent.<ref name=":7" /> A collaboration album with rapper [[Mac Miller]] was also teased in August 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/post-malone-mac-miller-might-releasing-joint-album-2363334 |title=Post Malone and Mac Miller might be releasing a joint album – NME |date=August 4, 2018 |work=NME|access-date=August 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180813210809/https://www.nme.com/news/music/post-malone-mac-miller-might-releasing-joint-album-2363334|archive-date=August 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> During his appearance on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'', he previewed his song "[[Sunflower (Post Malone and Swae Lee song)|Sunflower]]", a collaboration with [[Swae Lee]], from the soundtrack to the film ''[[Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kaufman |first=Gil |title=Post Malone Previews 'Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse' Track, Talks Justin Bieber Tattoo Rivalry on 'Tonight Show': Watch |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8477923/tonight-show-post-malone-previews-spider-man-track-talks-justin-bieber-watch |access-date=October 2, 2018 |magazine=Billboard |date=October 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003120212/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8477923/tonight-show-post-malone-previews-spider-man-track-talks-justin-bieber-watch|archive-date=October 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Blistein |first=Jon |title=Post Malone Previews New 'Spiderman' Song 'Sunflower' on 'Fallon' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-news/post-malone-preview-new-song-talk-tattoos-fallon-731835/ |access-date=October 2, 2018 |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=October 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002215201/https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-news/post-malone-preview-new-song-talk-tattoos-fallon-731835/|archive-date=October 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In November 2018, it was confirmed Malone was recording his third album in his Utah home.<ref name="Us Weekly">{{Cite news |url=https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/post-malone-and-girlfriend-ashlen-diaz-split-after-three-years/ |title=Post Malone and Girlfriend Ashlen Diaz Split After Three Years |date=November 2, 2018 |work=Us Weekly|access-date=November 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103091859/https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/post-malone-and-girlfriend-ashlen-diaz-split-after-three-years/|archive-date=November 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

Malone was nominated for 4 awards at the [[61st Grammy Awards]] for his album ''Beerbongs & Bentleys''. Among the nominations were [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]. He performed with the [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]] at the awards show on February 10, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Post Malone and Red Hot Chili Peppers to Perform Together at 2019 Grammys |url=https://www.spin.com/2019/01/post-malone-red-hot-chili-peppers-2019-grammys/ |work=Spin |date=January 24, 2019 |access-date=January 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125022029/https://www.spin.com/2019/01/post-malone-red-hot-chili-peppers-2019-grammys/|archive-date=January 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Red Hot Chili Peppers and Post Malone team up at 2019 Grammys: Watch |url=https://www.lyricsjoint.com/post-malone-red-hot-chilli-peppers-stay-rockstar-dark-necessities/|publisher=LyricsJoint |date=February 11, 2019 |access-date=February 11, 2019 }}</ref> In July 2019, Malone released the single "[[Goodbyes (Post Malone song)|Goodbyes]]" (featuring [[Young Thug]]), and also announced the [[Runaway Tour (Post Malone tour)|Runaway Tour]] with Swae Lee as the opener.<ref>{{cite web |title=Post Malone Tour Guide: Runaway Setlist, Tickets, Media |url=https://stadiumhelp.com/tour_guide/post-malone-tour-setlist-tickets/ |work=Stadium Help |date=July 15, 2019 |access-date=July 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418183233/https://stadiumhelp.com/tour_guide/post-malone-tour-setlist-tickets/|archive-date=April 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On August 5, Malone shared a snippet of an unreleased track "[[Circles (Post Malone song)|Circles]]" on [[YouTube]]. He then performed the song at his second annual ''Bud Light: Dive Bar'' concert and confirmed that the official song would be released the following week.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tVsqg2rNymc |title=Post Malone "Circles" Teaser |via=YouTube |date=August 5, 2019 |access-date=August 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806194210/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tVsqg2rNymc|archive-date=August 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> That same day and on July 25, 2019, at [[Cheyenne Frontier Days]] he announced the album was finished.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2019/7/post-malone-new-album-finished-details|title=Post Malone Reveals He Has Finished Recording His New Album|website=HYPEBEAST|date=July 26, 2019|access-date=March 21, 2020|archive-date=March 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321002912/https://hypebeast.com/2019/7/post-malone-new-album-finished-details|url-status=live}}</ref> He released the song on August 30, 2019.<ref name="Aniftos">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8528658/post-malone-circles-single-release-date |title=Post Malone Announces 'Circles' Single Release Date |magazine=Billboard |last=Aniftos |first=Rania |date=August 28, 2019 |access-date=August 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190829041906/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8528658/post-malone-circles-single-release-date|archive-date=August 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He confirmed that his upcoming third studio album will be released on September 6, 2019.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/08/06/post-malone-third-album-september-release-date-circles-snippet|title=Post Malone says his third album is dropping in September, shares new snippet|website=[[The Fader]]|last=Darville|first=Jordan|date=August 6, 2019|access-date=August 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806223340/https://www.thefader.com/2019/08/06/post-malone-third-album-september-release-date-circles-snippet|archive-date=August 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://thesource.com/2019/07/27/post-malone-announces-his-new-album-is-complete/ |title=Post Malone Announces His New Album is Complete |first=Shawn |last=Grant |website=[[The Source]] |date=July 27, 2019|access-date=August 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824184327/http://thesource.com/2019/07/27/post-malone-announces-his-new-album-is-complete/|archive-date=August 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On August 26, 2019, Malone announced on [[Twitter]] that his third album is called ''[[Hollywood's Bleeding]]'' and would be released on September 6, 2019.<ref>{{citation|url=https://tonedeaf.thebrag.com/post-malone-new-album-hollywoods-bleeding/|title=Post Malone formally announces upcoming album, 'Hollywood's Bleeding'|website=Tone Deaf|last=Jenke|first=Tyler|date=August 27, 2019|access-date=August 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827142605/https://tonedeaf.thebrag.com/post-malone-new-album-hollywoods-bleeding/|archive-date=August 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Aniftos" /> The album debuted at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200, selling 489,000 [[album-equivalent unit]]s in its first week.<ref>{{Cite magazine|title=Post Malone Scores Second No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 With 'Hollywood's Bleeding'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8530004/post-malone-hollywoods-bleeding-No1-debut-billboard-200-chart|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=September 15, 2019|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214192922/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8530004/post-malone-hollywoods-bleeding-No1-debut-billboard-200-chart|archive-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref>  ''Hollywood's Bleeding'' would also go on to be nominated for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] at the [[63rd Annual Grammy Awards|63rd Grammys.]]

===2020–2022: Collaborations, hiatus, and ''Twelve Carat Toothache''===
{{Main|Twelve Carat Toothache|}}
[[File:Post Malone in Chicago 2020.jpg|thumb|Malone performing in [[Rosemont, Illinois]] in February 2020|upright|left]]
On March 12, 2020, Malone's concert at [[Denver]]'s [[Pepsi Center]] proceeded as scheduled, drawing a sellout-crowd of 20,000, likely the last large-scale enclosed gathering in the U.S. before [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United States|COVID-19 pandemic lockdowns]].<ref>{{Cite magazine|date=May–June 2020|title=Colorado COVID-19 Timeline|url=http://digital.cobizmag.com/2020/MJ20/|magazine=ColoradoBiz|volume=47|pages=21|access-date=May 27, 2020|archive-date=June 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200605193213/http://digital.cobizmag.com/2020/MJ20/|url-status=live}}</ref> Malone received backlash for not cancelling his sold-out arena show amid rising concerns over the [[COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Skinner|first=Tom|date=March 14, 2020|title=Post Malone criticised for not cancelling arena show amid coronavirus crisis|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/post-malone-criticised-for-not-cancelling-arena-show-amid-coronavirus-crisis-2625378|url-status=live|access-date=March 15, 2020|website=[[NME]]|archive-date=March 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329055304/https://www.nme.com/news/music/post-malone-criticised-for-not-cancelling-arena-show-amid-coronavirus-crisis-2625378}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Osei|first=Sarah|date=March 14, 2020|title=People Are Upset at Post Malone for not Canceling His Sold-Out Show|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/post-malone-arena-show-coronavirus/|access-date=March 15, 2020|website=[[Highsnobiety]]}}</ref> Reportedly, future U.S. tour dates in March were postponed by [[Live Nation (events promoter)|Live Nation]] on March 12, 2020.<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Brooks|first=Dave|date=March 12, 2020|title=AEG & Live Nation Recommend Halting All Tours|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/touring/9333998/aeg-live-nation-recommend-halting-all-tours|url-status=live|access-date=March 15, 2020|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|archive-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314093918/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/touring/9333998/aeg-live-nation-recommend-halting-all-tours}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Knopper|first=Steve|date=March 13, 2020|title=Post Malone & Billie Eilish Sneak In Final Shows Before Coronavirus Cancellations – Critics Be Damned|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/touring/9335101/post-malone-billie-eilish-final-shows-coronavirus-cancellations-critics|url-status=live|access-date=March 15, 2020|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|archive-date=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315120722/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/touring/9335101/post-malone-billie-eilish-final-shows-coronavirus-cancellations-critics}}</ref>

On April 24, 2020, Malone announced that a new album was in progress during a livestream performance.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Coleman|first=C. Vernon II|title=Post Malone Wants to Put His New Album Out "As Soon as F***ing Possible"|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2020/04/post-malone-new-album-as-soon-as-possible/|access-date=April 26, 2020|website=XXL Mag|date=April 25, 2020 |archive-date=April 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200426162921/https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2020/04/post-malone-new-album-as-soon-as-possible/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Lavin|first=Will|date=April 27, 2020|title=Post Malone gives fans update on his next album|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/post-malone-gives-fans-update-on-new-album-2654637|access-date=May 7, 2020|work=[[NME]]|archive-date=May 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200505055135/https://www.nme.com/news/music/post-malone-gives-fans-update-on-new-album-2654637|url-status=live}}</ref> In late April 2020, Malone performed a live-streamed set consisting entirely of [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] covers from his home.<ref name="Nirvana">{{cite web |last1=Newstead |first1=Al |title=Post Malone's Nirvana Tribute livestream was pretty damn good, actually |url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/post-malone-nirvana-tribute-livestream-review-kurt-cobain/12189506 |website=triple j |date=April 27, 2020 |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |access-date=29 September 2020 |archive-date=January 25, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210125174324/https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/post-malone-nirvana-tribute-livestream-review-kurt-cobain/12189506 |url-status=live }}</ref> Malone sang lead vocals and provided rhythm guitar for the set. He was accompanied by drummer [[Travis Barker]], bassist [[Brian Lee (songwriter)|Brian Lee]] and lead guitarist Nick Mac. The performance raised over US$5 million for the [[World Health Organization]]'s COVID-19 relief fund.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greenwood |first1=Koltan |title=Here's how much money Post Malone's Nirvana tribute has already raised |url=https://www.altpress.com/news/post-malone-nirvana-livstream-raises-millions/ |website=Alternative Press |date=April 28, 2020 |access-date=29 September 2020 |archive-date=September 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200929000302/https://www.altpress.com/news/post-malone-nirvana-livstream-raises-millions/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The performance also received praise from Nirvana's surviving members [[Krist Novoselic]]<ref name="Nirvana" /> and [[Dave Grohl]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bruce |first1=Jasper |title=Dave Grohl says Post Malone's Nirvana livestream "sounded great" |url=https://www.nme.com/en_au/news/music/dave-grohl-says-post-malones-nirvana-live-stream-sounded-great-2665910 |website=NME |date=May 11, 2020 |publisher=BandLab Technologies |access-date=29 September 2020 |archive-date=August 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200804223917/https://www.nme.com/en_au/news/music/dave-grohl-says-post-malones-nirvana-live-stream-sounded-great-2665910 |url-status=live }}</ref> as well as [[Kurt Cobain]]'s widow [[Courtney Love]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Acquilina |first1=Tyler |title=Courtney Love, Krist Novoselic react to Post Malone's Nirvana tribute concert: 'Goosebumps!' |url=https://ew.com/music/post-malone-nirvana-coronavirus-concert-courtney-love-krist-novoselic/ |magazine=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=29 September 2020 |archive-date=August 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200813061946/https://ew.com/music/post-malone-nirvana-coronavirus-concert-courtney-love-krist-novoselic/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In June 2020, Malone featured on [[Tyla Yaweh]]'s single, "[[Tommy Lee (song)|Tommy Lee]]". The single was followed up with a remix, released July 10, 2020, featuring drums from [[Tommy Lee]] himself, as well as a re-recorded guitar instrumental.<ref>{{Cite web|date=July 10, 2020|title=Tommy Lee joins Post Malone and Tyla Yaweh on remix of "Tommy Lee": Stream|url=https://consequence.net/2020/07/tommy-lee-drums-on-remix-of-tommy-lee-song-by-tyla-yaweh-and-post-malone-stream/|access-date=August 18, 2020|website=Consequence of Sound|language=en-US|archive-date=September 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200913204324/https://consequence.net/2020/07/tommy-lee-drums-on-remix-of-tommy-lee-song-by-tyla-yaweh-and-post-malone-stream/|url-status=live}}</ref> A second remix to the song, featuring rapper [[Saint Jhn]], was released subsequently.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tyla-yaweh-drops-another-tommy-lee-remix-with-post-malone-and-saint-jhn-new-song.1988421.html|title=Tyla Yaweh Drops Another "Tommy Lee" Remix With Post Malone & SAINt JHN|website=HotNewHipHop|date=August 28, 2020|access-date=February 16, 2021|archive-date=June 9, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210609171338/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tyla-yaweh-drops-another-tommy-lee-remix-with-post-malone-and-saint-jhn-new-song.1988421.html|url-status=live}}</ref> On April 30, 2021, Malone was featured on [[DJ Khaled]]'s twelfth studio album ''[[Khaled Khaled]]'' on the song "[[I Did It (DJ Khaled song)|I Did It]]" also featuring [[DaBaby]], [[Megan Thee Stallion]], and [[Lil Baby]].

On July 9, 2021, Malone released the single "[[Motley Crew (song)|Motley Crew]]" with an accompanying music video, featuring several guest stars, past collaborators and friends including [[Tommy Lee]], [[Tyga]], [[Tyla Yaweh]] and his manager Dre London. The music video was directed by [[Cole Bennett]] of Lyrical Lemonade. On November 5, Malone released "[[One Right Now]]" with [[the Weeknd]], as the lead single from his upcoming fourth studio album.<ref>{{Cite magazine|first=Darlene|last=Aderoju|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/the-weeknd-post-malone-one-right-now-music-video-9660286/|title=Watch The Weeknd & Post Malone Duel to the Death in Bloody 'One Right Now' Music Video|magazine=Billboard|date=November 15, 2021|access-date=January 26, 2022|language=en-US|archive-date=January 26, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220126172507/https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/the-weeknd-post-malone-one-right-now-music-video-9660286/|url-status=live}}</ref> On January 26, 2022, during his cover story will ''Billboard'', Malone revealed that his fourth studio album would be titled ''[[Twelve Carat Toothache]]''.<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Havens|first=Lyndsey|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/features/post-malone-billboard-cover-story-2022-interview-1235022091/|title=Post Malone Is Done Compromising: The Superstar Gets Real at His Mountain Hideaway|date=January 26, 2022|access-date=January 26, 2022|magazine=Billboard|language=en-US|archive-date=January 26, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220126150935/https://www.billboard.com/music/features/post-malone-billboard-cover-story-2022-interview-1235022091/|url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2022, Republic Records relaunched [[Mercury Records]] with a new roster that includes Post Malone.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Jem|last=Aswad|url=https://variety.com/2022/music/news/republic-relaunches-mercury-records-post-malone-1235230034/|title=Republic Relaunches Mercury Records; Post Malone, James Bay Move Over to New Roster|website=Variety|date=April 11, 2022|access-date=April 11, 2022|language=en-US|archive-date=April 11, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220411170043/https://variety.com/2022/music/news/republic-relaunches-mercury-records-post-malone-1235230034/|url-status=live}}</ref> On April 27, 2022, Post revealed that ''Twelve Carat Toothache'' would be released June 3, 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Matthew|last=Strauss|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/post-malone-reveals-release-date-for-new-album-twelve-carat-toothache/|title=Post Malone Reveals Release Date for New Album Twelve Carat Toothache|website=Pitchfork|date=April 27, 2022|access-date=April 27, 2022|language=en-US|archive-date=April 28, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220428105151/https://pitchfork.com/news/post-malone-reveals-release-date-for-new-album-twelve-carat-toothache/|url-status=live}}</ref>  Malone released the album's second single, "[[Cooped Up]]" with [[Roddy Ricch]], on May 12, 2022.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.billboard.com/music/rb-hip-hop/post-malone-roddy-ricch-cooped-up-video-1235070213/ | title=Post Malone & Roddy Ricch Join Forces in Vibey 'Cooped Up' Video: Watch | magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | access-date=May 13, 2022 | archive-date=June 3, 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220603234034/https://www.billboard.com/music/rb-hip-hop/post-malone-roddy-ricch-cooped-up-video-1235070213/ | url-status=live }}</ref>

On May 14, 2022, he appeared as a musical guest on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' and performed "Cooped Up" with Ricch, as well as an unreleased song titled "Love/Hate Letter to Alcohol", in which he was joined by [[Fleet Foxes]]. Malone had previously confirmed that he had worked with Fleet Foxes frontman [[Robin Pecknold]] on a song for the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/post-malone-joined-by-fleet-foxes-and-roddy-ricch-for-saturday-night-live-performance-3225700|title=Post Malone joined by Fleet Foxes and Roddy Ricch for 'Saturday Night Live' performance|last=Richards|first=Will|website=[[NME]]|date=May 15, 2022|access-date=May 15, 2022|archive-date=May 15, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220515080017/https://www.nme.com/news/music/post-malone-joined-by-fleet-foxes-and-roddy-ricch-for-saturday-night-live-performance-3225700|url-status=live}}</ref>

For the 2022 film ''[[Chip 'n Dale: Rescue Rangers (film)|Chip 'n Dale: Rescue Rangers]]'', Malone covered the theme song from the [[Chip 'n Dale: Rescue Rangers (TV series)|1989 television series of the same name]], originally performed by [[Jeff Pescetto]] in the series and by The Jets in album releases.

On August 12, 2022, the documentary film ''Runaway'' premiered on the [[Amazon Prime Video]] channel Freevee.  It showed behind the scenes moments from the first leg of the Runaway Tour in 2019, as well as performances from some of the highlighted dates, such as New York City, Chicago, and the 2019 Posty Fest in Arlington.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.iconvsicon.com/2022/07/30/post-malone-runaway-documentary-to-debut-august-12th-via-amazon-freevee/ | title='Post Malone: Runaway' Documentary to Debut August 12th Via Amazon Freevee | date=July 30, 2022 | access-date=August 12, 2022 | archive-date=August 16, 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220816224425/https://www.iconvsicon.com/2022/07/30/post-malone-runaway-documentary-to-debut-august-12th-via-amazon-freevee/ | url-status=live }}</ref>

===2023: ''The Diamond Collection'' and ''Austin''===
{{Main|The Diamond Collection|Austin (album)}}

In April 2023, Malone announced that he was working on a new album. On April 14, Malone released "[[Chemical (Post Malone song)|Chemical]]", as the lead single from his upcoming fifth studio album.<ref>{{cite web|first=Carys|last=Anderson|url=https://consequence.net/2023/04/post-malone-chemical-stream/|title=Post Malone Kicks Off His Next Era with New Song "Chemical": Stream|work=[[Consequence (publication)|Consequence]]|date=April 14, 2023|access-date=April 20, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Zach|last=Dionne|url=https://www.complex.com/music/post-malone-chemical-video|title=Post Malone Releases New Song and Video "Chemical"|work=Complex|date=April 13, 2023|access-date=April 20, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|first=Daniel|last=Kreps|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/post-malone-new-single-chemical-1234714652/amp/|title=Post Malone Drops New Single 'Chemical,' First New Music of 2023|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=April 14, 2023|access-date=April 20, 2023}}</ref>  On April 21, 2023, Malone released ''[[The Diamond Collection]]'', a nine-song compilation of his record-breaking eight [[RIAA]] Diamond-certified singles, along with the single "Chemical".<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Lars|last=Brandle|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/awards/post-malone-riaa-the-diamond-collection-1235309900/|title=Post Malone Bags RIAA Records, Sets 'The Diamond Collection'|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=April 20, 2023|access-date=April 21, 2023}}</ref> On April 21, 2023, alongside [[The Kid Laroi]], Malone appeared on "[[What You Say (YoungBoy Never Broke Again song)|What You Say]]", the twenty-fourth cut of [[YoungBoy Never Broke Again]]'s sixth full-length studio album, ''[[Don't Try This at Home (YoungBoy Never Broke Again album)|Don't Try This At Home]]''.<ref>{{cite web|first=Alexander|last=Cole|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/664275-nba-youngboy-post-malone-the-kid-laroi-single|title=NBA YoungBoy Enlists Post Malone & The Kid LAROI On "What You Say"|work=[[HotNewHipHop]]|date=April 22, 2023|access-date=April 23, 2023|archive-date=April 23, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230423215039/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/664275-nba-youngboy-post-malone-the-kid-laroi-single|url-status=live}}</ref>

On May 16, 2023, Malone announced that his fifth studio album, ''[[Austin (album)|Austin]]'', would be released on July 28, 2023. On May 19, "[[Mourning (Post Malone song)|Mourning]]" was released as the second single from the album.<ref>{{cite web|first=Gabriel|last=Bras Nevares|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/677144-post-malone-austin-new-album|title=Post Malone Announces New Album ''Austin''|work=[[HotNewHipHop]]|date=May 16, 2023|access-date=May 16, 2023}}</ref> On July 14, the third single, "[[Overdrive (Post Malone song)|Overdrive]]", was released.<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Joshua|last=Espinoza|url=https://www.complex.com/music/a/joshua-espinoza/post-malone-overdrive|title=Post Malone Drops ew Single "Overdrive"|magazine=[[Complex Networks|Complex]]|date=July 14, 2023|access-date=July 14, 2023}}</ref> On September 8, the fourth single "[[Enough Is Enough (Post Malone song)|Enough Is Enough]]" was released.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Post Malone – Enough Is Enough (Radio Date: 08-09-2023) |url=https://www.earone.it/news/post_malone_enough_is_enough_radio_date_08_09_2023_78943452/ |access-date=2024-01-04 |website=EarOne|date=September 4, 2023 }}</ref> On July 17, 2023, Malone collaborated with [[Noah Kahan]] on a re-released version of Kahan's single "[[Dial Drunk]]" featuring a new vocal from Malone. The song charted on the [[Billboard Hot 100]] reaching a peak of number 25.<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=Noah Kahan {{!}} Biography, Music & News |url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/noah-kahan/ |access-date=2024-01-13 |magazine=Billboard |language=en-US}}</ref>

===2024–present: ''F-1 Trillion''===
{{Main|F-1 Trillion}}

On February 11, 2024, Malone performed "[[America the Beautiful]]" at the [[Super Bowl LVIII]].<ref name=":8">{{Cite magazine |last1=Yandoli |first1=Tomás Mier,Krystie Lee |last2=Mier |first2=Tomás |last3=Yandoli |first3=Krystie Lee |date=2024-02-11 |title=Post Malone Performs 'America the Beautiful' at the Super Bowl |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/post-malone-super-bowl-2024-performance-america-the-beautiful-1234964636/ |access-date=2024-02-12 |magazine=Rolling Stone |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=":9">{{Cite magazine |last=Lamarre |first=Carl |date=2024-02-12 |title=Post Malone Brings Out His Guitar for Stirring 'America the Beautiful' Performance at the 2024 Super Bowl |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/post-malone-sings-america-the-beautiful-super-bowl-2024-1235605089/ |access-date=2024-02-12 |magazine=Billboard |language=en-US}}</ref> On February 5, the tracklist for [[Taylor Swift]]'s 11th studio album, ''[[The Tortured Poets Department]]'', was revealed via her social media accounts, featuring Malone on the first track "[[Fortnight (Taylor Swift song)|Fortnight]]". He later made a post on his social media supporting this.<ref>{{Cite web |first=Nina |last=Corcoran |title=Taylor Swift Unveils Tracklist for The Tortured Poets Department |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/taylor-swift-unveils-tracklist-for-the-tortured-poets-department/ |date=February 5, 2024 |access-date=February 6, 2024}}</ref> The album was released on April 19, 2024, with "Fortnight" being chosen as the lead single and the music video being released later that day. On the day of its release, "Fortnight" set the [[List of Spotify streaming records|single-day streaming record for any song on Spotify]], surpassing the all-time peak previously held by [[Mariah Carey]]'s song "[[All I Want for Christmas Is You|All I Want For Christmas Is You]]" (1994).<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Batey |first=Eve |date=2024-04-20 |title=Taylor Swift Smashes Several Spotify Records in Single Day |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/culture/story/taylor-swift-tortured-poets-tortured-poets-department-fortnight-spotify-records |access-date=2024-04-20 |magazine=Vanity Fair |language=en-US}}</ref>

On March 29, 2024, Malone was featured on the track "Levii's Jeans" off [[Beyoncé]]'s eighth studio album, ''[[Cowboy Carter]]''.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Zemler |first=Emily |date=2024-03-29 |title=Beyoncé, Post Malone Celebrate Cowboy Couture on 'Levii's Jeans' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/beyonce-post-malone-leviis-jeans-cowboy-carter-1234996387/ |access-date=2024-03-29 |magazine=Rolling Stone |language=en-US}}</ref> On May 2, 2024, Malone announced his next single, entitled "[[I Had Some Help]]" featuring [[Morgan Wallen]], which released on May 10.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=postmalone|number=1786149057842344340|title=I Had Some Help. May 10th @MorganWallen|date=May 2, 2024|access-date=May 3, 2024}}</ref> The song earned 167 first-week adds at country radio, making it the second song in history to clear the panel in its first week after [[Garth Brooks]] in 1997 with "[[Longneck Bottle]]".<ref name="Music Row">{{cite web|url=https://musicrow.com/2024/05/morgan-wallen-post-malone-make-history-with-i-had-some-help/|title=Morgan Wallen & Post Malone Make History With 'I Had Some Help'|author=Lorie Hollabaugh|date=May 14, 2024|website=Music Row|access-date=May 14, 2024}}</ref> It also broke [[Spotify]]'s single-day country streaming record with nearly 14 million streams, debuted at No. 1 on the streaming platform's Global Daily chart and became its top male collaboration debut of all time, in addition to topping [[Apple Music]]'s Global chart and [[Pandora (service)|Pandora]]'s Top Thumb Hundred chart, upon release.<ref name="Music Row"/> It debuted at No. 18 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Country Airplay]] chart.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2024/05/14/post-malones-new-single-helps-him-hit-a-new-chart-highafter-just-a-few-days/?sh=1895bb9d5891|title=Post Malone's New Single Helps Him Hit A New Chart High–After Just A Few Days|author=Hugh McIntyre|date=May 14, 2024|magazine=[[Forbes]]|access-date=May 14, 2024}}</ref>

On June 13, 2024, Malone announced the single "[[Pour Me a Drink]]" featuring [[Blake Shelton]]. It was released on June 21.<ref>{{cite web|first=Maxim|last=Mower|url=https://holler.country/news/breaking/post-malone-and-blake-shelton-confirm-release-date-for-viral-collaboration-pour-me-a-drink/|title=Post Malone and Blake Shelton Confirm Release Date for Viral Collaboration, 'Pour me a Drink'|work=Holler Country|date=June 14, 2024|access-date=June 18, 2024}}</ref> 

On June 18, 2024, Malone announced his sixth studio album, ''[[F-1 Trillion]]'', which was released on August 16, 2024.<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Jessica|last=Nicholson|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/post-malone-reveals-album-title-release-date-1235713136/|title=Post Malone Announces 'F-1 Trillion' Album & Release Date|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=June 18, 2024|access-date=June 18, 2024}}</ref> On July 26, Malone released the third single from the album "Guy For That" featuring [[Luke Combs]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Mier |first=Tomás |date=2024-07-26 |title=Post Malone Enlists Luke Combs for Another Country Duet, 'Guy for That' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/post-malone-luke-combs-guy-for-that-song-1235068118/ |access-date=2024-07-28 |magazine=Rolling Stone |language=en-US}}</ref>

==Musical style==
Malone's music is [[Hip hop music|hip hop]],<ref name=":usa today genres"/><ref>{{cite web|first=Rabab|last=Al-Sharif|url=https://loudwire.com/post-malone-high-school-metalcore-band/|title=Did You Know Post Malone Used to Be in a Metal Band?|work=[[Loudwire]]|date=January 17, 2019|access-date=June 26, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240511130326/https://loudwire.com/post-malone-high-school-metalcore-band/|archive-date=May 11, 2024|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|first=Hua|last=Hsu|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/05/14/post-malones-white-rapper-blues|title=Post Malone's White-Rapper Blues|magazine=[[The New Yorker]]|date=May 7, 2018|access-date=April 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200528032639/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/05/14/post-malones-white-rapper-blues|archive-date=May 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Pop music|pop]],<ref name=":usa today genres">{{cite news|first=Melissa|last=Ruggieri|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/music/2024/02/07/post-malone-best-songs/72504015007/|title=Post Malone is singing at Super Bowl 58: Get to know five of his best songs|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=February 7, 2024|access-date=June 26, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240420051750/https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/music/2024/02/07/post-malone-best-songs/72504015007/|archive-date=April 20, 2024|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":newyorker genres">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/listening-booth/post-malones-languid-songs-of-self-loathing|title=Post Malone's Languid Songs of Self-Loathing|magazine=[[The New Yorker]]|date=June 9, 2022|access-date=July 28, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220728034100/https://www.newyorker.com/culture/listening-booth/post-malones-languid-songs-of-self-loathing|archive-date=July 28, 2022|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Kelefa|last=Sanneh|url=https://www.gq.com/story/post-malone-cover-2020/amp|title=How Post Malone Became Pop's King of Heartbreak|work=[[GQ (website)|GQ]]|date=March 2, 2020|access-date=May 15, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220515163100/https://www.gq.com/story/post-malone-cover-2020/amp|archive-date=May 15, 2022|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]],<ref name=":usa today genres"/> [[Trap music|trap]],<ref name=":newyorker genres"/> [[pop-rap]],<ref>{{cite web|first=Luca|last=Cimarusti|url=http://chicagoreader.com/music/hip-hop-goes-pop-with-swae-lee-and-post-malone/|title=Hip-hop goes pop with Swae Lee and Post Malone|newspaper=[[Chicago Reader]]|date= February 1, 2020|access-date=September 26, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210925131348/https://chicagoreader.com/music/hip-hop-goes-pop-with-swae-lee-and-post-malone/|archive-date=September 25, 2021|url-status=live}}</ref> [[pop rock]],<ref>{{cite news|first=Helen|last=Brown|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/post-malone-austin-review-album-b2387030.html|title=Post Malone, Austin review: Good lines get lost in the sludge of pop-rock formula and mid-tempo pacing|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=August 3, 2023|access-date=June 26, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240326104127/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/post-malone-austin-review-album-b2387030.html|archive-date=March 26, 2024|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Country music|country]],<ref>{{cite web|first=Joyce|last=Li|url=https://hypebeast.com/2024/8/pos-malone-country-album-f-1-trillion-tracklist-dolly-parton-tim-mcgraw-blake-shelton-brad-paisley-chris-stapleton-morgan-wallen-luke-combs-announcement|title=Post Malone Reveals Tracklist for New Country Album 'F-1 Trillion'|work=Hypebeast|date=August 1, 2024|access-date=August 6, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240801061906/https://hypebeast.com/2024/8/pos-malone-country-album-f-1-trillion-tracklist-dolly-parton-tim-mcgraw-blake-shelton-brad-paisley-chris-stapleton-morgan-wallen-luke-combs-announcement|archive-date=August 1, 2024|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Jon|last=Pareles|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2024/05/10/arts/music/playlist-post-malone-morgan-wallen-willow.html|title=Post Malone Goes Country With Morgan Wallen, and 8 More New Songs|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 10, 2024|access-date=August 6, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240605005335/https://www.nytimes.com/2024/05/10/arts/music/playlist-post-malone-morgan-wallen-willow.html|archive-date=June 5, 2024|url-status=live}}</ref> [[indie pop]],<ref>{{cite web|first=Molly|last=Cantwell|url=https://www.hotpress.com/music/album-review-post-malone-austin-22982079|title=Album Review: Post Malone, Austin|work=Hot Press|date=July 31, 2023|access-date=June 26, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230802131733/https://www.hotpress.com/music/album-review-post-malone-austin-22982079|archive-date=August 2, 2023|url-status=live}}</ref> [[rap rock]],<ref>{{cite web|first=Brandon|last=Friederich|url=https://www.maxim.com/entertainment/post-malone-breaks-beatles-record-2018-5|title=Post Malone Just Smashed A Record Held By The Beatles Since 1964|date=May 9, 2018|access-date=October 14, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015004538/https://www.maxim.com/entertainment/post-malone-breaks-beatles-record-2018-5|archive-date=October 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[cloud rap]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://celebrityinsider.org/airplane-carrying-cloud-rap-singer-post-malone-lands-safely-after-two-of-its-tires-explode-182498/|title=Cloud rap singer lands safely after 2 tires explode|work=Celebrity Insider|year=2018|access-date=November 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127110245/http://celebrityinsider.org/airplane-carrying-cloud-rap-singer-post-malone-lands-safely-after-two-of-its-tires-explode-182498/|archive-date=November 27, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Malone's music has been described as a "melting pot of the country, [[grunge]] and hip hop"<ref name="clashmusic">{{Cite news|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/features/facing-the-music-with-post-malone|title=Facing The Music With Post Malone|work=Clash Magazine|access-date=August 7, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808044448/http://www.clashmusic.com/features/facing-the-music-with-post-malone|archive-date=August 8, 2017}}</ref> and Malone himself has been described as versatile.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://thedmonline.com/stoney-album-showcases-post-malones-unique-musical-style/ |title=Stoney album showcases Post Malone's unique musical style |date=January 4, 2017 |work=The Daily Mississippian|access-date=August 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808040818/http://thedmonline.com/stoney-album-showcases-post-malones-unique-musical-style/|archive-date=August 8, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> His vocal style has been described as "[[wiktionary:laconic|laconic]]".<ref name="Post Malone's Stoney Review">{{Cite news|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malones-stoney-review-news.26332.html?|title=Post Malone's "Stoney" (Review)|work=HotNewHipHop|access-date=August 7, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808032821/http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malones-stoney-review-news.26332.html|archive-date=August 8, 2017}}</ref> Jon Caramanica of ''[[The New York Times]]'' described Malone as "an artist who toes the line between singing and rapping, and hip-hop and spooky electric folk".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Caramanica |first1=Jon |title=White Rappers, Clear of a Black Planet |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/21/arts/music/white-rappers-geazy-mike-stud.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=November 18, 2017 |date=August 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105193625/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/21/arts/music/white-rappers-geazy-mike-stud.html|archive-date=November 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Malone himself has called his music "genre-less".

Malone cites [[Bob Dylan]], in whom he became interested around the age of 15, as an influence on his music, calling him "a genius" and "a god" though his music has been called "about as far away from Rock n' Roll as you can get".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malone-joins-band-performs-elvis-presley-covers-at-a-nashville-bar-news.49692.html |title=Post Malone Joins Band, Performs Elvis Presley Covers At A Nashville Bar |work=HotNewHipHop|access-date=June 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612135931/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malone-joins-band-performs-elvis-presley-covers-at-a-nashville-bar-news.49692.html|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He called "[[Subterranean Homesick Blues]]" the "first rap song". He has a tattoo of Dylan as well.<ref name="papermag" /> Malone has cited [[Kurt Cobain]] and [[Johnny Cash]] as key influences too.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4G6PZIhrXKQ |title=Post Malone Answering Fans Questions (minute 4:30 for influences) |website=YouTube |date=February 6, 2017 |access-date=June 12, 2019 |archive-date=August 28, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210828051331/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4G6PZIhrXKQ |url-status=live }}</ref> Malone has also cited [[50 Cent]], whom he called a legend,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8221238/post-malone-montreality-interview |title=Post Malone Calls U.S. Government a 'Reality Show' & Praises 50 Cent as 'Legendary' in 'MONTREALITY' Interview |magazine=Billboard|access-date=March 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304061534/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8221238/post-malone-montreality-interview|archive-date=March 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Kanye West]] and Key! as influences.<ref name=":6" />

==Relationship with the hip hop community==
Malone has been called a "culture vulture" multiple times by different publications and on social media<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://thesource.com/2017/11/22/black-twitter-calls-post-malone-culture-vulture-dragging-begins/ |title=Black Twitter Calls Post Malone a 'Culture Vulture', Dragging Begins |date=November 22, 2017 |work=The Source|access-date=March 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301104135/http://thesource.com/2017/11/22/black-twitter-calls-post-malone-culture-vulture-dragging-begins/|archive-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://thatgrapejuice.net/2017/11/social-media-roasts-post-malone-hip-hop-diss/ |title=Social Media Roasts Post Malone After Hip-Hop Diss |date=November 21, 2017 |work=..::That Grape Juice.net::.. – Thirsty?|access-date=March 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301104428/http://thatgrapejuice.net/2017/11/social-media-roasts-post-malone-hip-hop-diss/|archive-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> for appropriating [[African-American culture]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.blerdsonline.com/2017/12/post-malone-essence-of-culture-vulture.html |title=Post Malone: The Essence of a Culture Vulture |work=Blerds Online|access-date=March 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301164509/http://www.blerdsonline.com/2017/12/post-malone-essence-of-culture-vulture.html|archive-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/oct/20/is-white-rapper-post-malone-post-racial-or-problematic |title=Post Malone: post-racial or problematic? |last=Iandoli |first=Kathy |date=October 20, 2017 |website=The Guardian|access-date=March 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301230552/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/oct/20/is-white-rapper-post-malone-post-racial-or-problematic|archive-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.datwav.com/post-malone-culture-vulture/|title=Is Post Malone a Culture Vulture?|date=November 28, 2017|work=DatWAV.com|access-date=March 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301164537/http://www.datwav.com/post-malone-culture-vulture/|archive-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> California rapper [[Lil B]] wrote on Twitter in October 2017: "Post Malone is slowly turning into a white dude! Lol he's pushing it, give it a few years he gon be full country and hate blacks lol", with Malone replying in an interview, claiming that his white skin has been "used against him".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://kollegekidd.com/news/post-malone-reacts-to-lil-b-calling-him-a-culture-vulture-says-his-white-skin-color-is-being-used-against-him/ |title=Post Malone Reacts To Lil B Calling Him A Culture Vulture, Says His White Skin Color Is Being Used Against Him|date=November 2, 2017|work=KollegeKidd.com|access-date=March 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301224833/http://kollegekidd.com/news/post-malone-reacts-to-lil-b-calling-him-a-culture-vulture-says-his-white-skin-color-is-being-used-against-him/|archive-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2018, Malone went on an intoxicated rant against people who describe him as a culture vulture.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/01/post-malone-fires-back-culture-vulture/ |title=Post Malone Fires Back at Critics Who Call Him a Culture Vulture |website=XXL Mag|date=January 29, 2018 |access-date=March 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301104141/http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/01/post-malone-fires-back-culture-vulture/|archive-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2018/01/post-malone-message-culture-vulture-critics |title=Post Malone Has a Message For All of His 'Culture Vulture' Critics |website=Complex|access-date=March 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301104115/http://www.complex.com/music/2018/01/post-malone-message-culture-vulture-critics|archive-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In an interview with ''GQ'' several days later, Malone said "there's a struggle being a white rapper."<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://hypebeast.com/2018/1/post-malone-culture-vulture-response |title=Post Malone Fires Back At 'Culture Vulture' Critics |work=HYPEBEAST|access-date=March 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301104128/https://hypebeast.com/2018/1/post-malone-culture-vulture-response|archive-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

In a November 2017 interview with Polish media outlet ''Newonce'', Malone said that modern hip-hop music lacks "people talking about real shit" and added that "if you're looking to think about life, don't listen to hip-hop."<ref name=":6">{{cite web |last1=Thompson |first1=Desire |title=Post Malone Doesn't Think Current Hip Hop Has Any Meaning |url=https://www.vibe.com/2017/11/post-malone-tells-people-dont-listen-to-hip-hop/ |website=Vibe (magazine) |access-date=November 22, 2017 |date=November 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171121204340/https://www.vibe.com/2017/11/post-malone-tells-people-dont-listen-to-hip-hop/|archive-date=November 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Dandridge-Lemco |first1=Ben |title=Post Malone: "If you're looking to think about life, don't listen to hip-hop" |url=https://www.thefader.com/2017/11/20/post-malone-polish-interview-dont-listen-to-hip-hop |website=The FADER |access-date=November 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122080644/http://www.thefader.com/2017/11/20/post-malone-polish-interview-dont-listen-to-hip-hop|archive-date=November 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He was criticized for his comments, including by fellow rappers Lil B and [[Vince Staples]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Geoff |title=Syracuse native Post Malone blames controversial hip-hop comments on alcohol |url=http://www.syracuse.com/celebrity-news/index.ssf/2017/11/post_malone_hip_hop_comments_alcohol.html |website=Syracuse.com |date=November 24, 2017 |access-date=November 25, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171124233655/http://www.syracuse.com/celebrity-news/index.ssf/2017/11/post_malone_hip_hop_comments_alcohol.html|archive-date=November 24, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Post Malone Blames Controversial Comments On The Alcohol: "I Love Hip-Hop" |url=https://www.bet.com/article/rnze8p/post-malone-blames-hip-hop-comments-on-the-alcohol |website=Bet.com|access-date=November 25, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201043842/https://www.bet.com/music/2017/11/24/post-malone-hip-hop-backlash-video-response.html|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Malone later appeared in a video on Twitter, saying that the reason for his comments was that it was a "beer-tasting" interview,<ref>{{cite web |title=Post Malone Says He Was Not Dissing Hip-Hop |url=http://www.tmz.com/2017/11/23/post-malone-hip-hop-comment-beer/ |website=Tmz.com|date=November 23, 2017 |access-date=November 25, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171125050434/http://www.tmz.com/2017/11/23/post-malone-hip-hop-comment-beer/|archive-date=November 25, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and going on to say that he loves hip-hop.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Darville |first1=Jordan |title=Post Malone addresses his controversial hip-hop comments and cultural appropriation in new video |url=https://www.thefader.com/2017/11/23/post-malone-hip-hop-comments-new-video-statement |website=The FADER |access-date=November 25, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171126070935/http://www.thefader.com/2017/11/23/post-malone-hip-hop-comments-new-video-statement|archive-date=November 26, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=C. Vernon |last=Coleman |title=Post Malone Expresses Love for Hip-Hop Following Backlash |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/11/post-malone-love-hip-hop-controversial-comments/ |website=XXLmag.com|date=November 23, 2017 |access-date=November 25, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171125082553/http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/11/post-malone-love-hip-hop-controversial-comments/|archive-date=November 25, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Newonce'', however, denied that claim, stating that Malone barely drank at all during the interview.<ref name="newonce">{{cite web |first=Trace William |last=Cowen |title=Post Malone Clears Up His Controversial Hip-Hop Comments: 'I Love Hip-Hop' (UPDATE) |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2017/11/post-malone-clarifies-hip-hop-comments |website=Complex|access-date=November 25, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171125012631/http://www.complex.com/music/2017/11/post-malone-clarifies-hip-hop-comments|archive-date=November 25, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In the follow-up Malone went on to say, "What I was saying was that when I wanna sit down and cry, I sit down and I listen to [[Bob Dylan]] and his guitar. Just like everyone else, no matter how hard you are, no matter where you're from, you're gonna have times where you sit back and reflect on your life and you listen to what you wanna listen to. For me, that's Bob Dylan."<ref name="newonce"/>

==Other ventures==
During Malone's [[Runaway Tour (Post Malone)|Runaway Tour]] in 2019, he released special-edition [[Bud Light]] beer cans at local stores in 15 cities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/arts-entertainment/pop-culture/2019/10/08/thats-post-malones-face-on-bud-light-cans-in-texas/|title=That's rapper Post Malone's face on Bud Light cans in Texas|website=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|date=October 8, 2019}}</ref> He also released multiple lines of sunglasses in collaboration with Arnette.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/pro/post-malone-x-arnette-sunglasses-collection/|title=Post Malone's Arnette Sunglasses Will Have You Looking Fly All Year Round|magazine=Billboard|date=November 5, 2019}}</ref>

Since 2018, he has released several collaborations with footwear company [[Crocs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2018/11/post-malone-crocs-dimitri-glog|title=Post Malone & Crocs Team up for a Surprising Collaboration|website=[[Hypebeast (company)|Hypebeast]]|date=November 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/rb-hip-hop/post-malone-crocs-sell-out-8490193/|title=Post Malone Crocs Collaboration Sells Out Minutes After Going on Sale|magazine=Billboard|date=December 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/style/article/post-malone-crocs-sold-out-trnd/index.html|title=Post Malone's Crocs sold out in under two hours|website=CNN|date=December 11, 2019}}</ref> The fifth and latest collaboration was released in December 2020. In May 2020, he launched his own line of French [[rosé]] wine, ''Maison No. 9'', named after his&nbsp;favourite tarot card, the [[Nine of Swords]].&nbsp;It sold out in two days upon being made available for sale.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malones-wine-sells-out-in-2-days-news.112908.html|title=Post Malone's Wine Sells Out In 2 Days|work=HotNewHipHop|date=June 20, 2020|access-date=June 20, 2020|archive-date=June 22, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200622015619/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malones-wine-sells-out-in-2-days-news.112908.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In August 2020, Post Malone invested in [[Envy Gaming]]. He became a co-owner of the organization.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Webster|first=Andrew|date=2020-08-28|title=Post Malone is now a co-owner of Texas' biggest esports teams|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/8/28/21406041/post-malone-envy-gaming-dallas-empire-fuel|access-date=2021-06-22|website=The Verge|language=en|archive-date=June 24, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210624204130/https://www.theverge.com/2020/8/28/21406041/post-malone-envy-gaming-dallas-empire-fuel|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Beresford|first=Trilby|date=2020-08-28|title=Post Malone Takes Equity Stake in Envy Gaming (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/music-news/post-malone-takes-equity-stake-in-envy-gaming-exclusive-4048842/|access-date=2021-06-22|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en-US|archive-date=June 24, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210624204428/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/music-news/post-malone-takes-equity-stake-in-envy-gaming-exclusive-4048842/|url-status=live}}</ref>

An enthusiast of the collectible trading card game ''[[Magic: The Gathering]]'', in 2022 he collaborated with publisher [[Wizards of the Coast]] to create two special supplemental sets: "Secret Lair x Post Malone: Backstage Pass", with cards featuring himself in the title and art, and "Secret Lair x Post Malone: The Lands", with cards featuring his tattoos in the art and flavor texts written by him.<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=Post the Gathering: Post Malone Teams Up With Magic: The Gathering To Release New Card Packs |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/product-recommendations/lifestyle/post-malone-magic-the-gathering-secret-lair-card-packs-1234608197/ |last=Anderson |first=Sage |date=2022-10-10 |access-date=2022-10-30 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |archive-date=October 30, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221030080953/https://www.rollingstone.com/product-recommendations/lifestyle/post-malone-magic-the-gathering-secret-lair-card-packs-1234608197/ |url-status=live }}</ref> He also owns the unique [[One Ring]] card, which he purchased for more than $2 million.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Jones |first=Dustin |date=2023-08-03 |title=Post Malone bought Magic: The Gathering's 'One Ring' card valued as high as $2 million |url=https://www.npr.org/2023/08/03/1191841285/post-malone-bought-magic-gathering-mtg-one-ring-card-million |access-date=2023-10-06 |website=NPR}}</ref>

In April 2023, Malone designed the exterior of a [[Raising Cane's Chicken Fingers|Raising Cane's]] restaurant location in [[Midvale, Utah]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sltrib.com/artsliving/2023/04/13/fans-throng-rapper-post-malone/|title=Fans throng rapper Post Malone at Utah fast-food location that he designed|website=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]|date=April 13, 2023}}</ref>

Malone is slated to appear in the [[professional wrestling]] video game ''[[WWE 2K24]]'' as a [[downloadable content|downloadable]] superstar as part of the game's [[Season pass (video games)|Season Pass]]. He also would curate the game's soundtrack.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lambert |first1=Jeremy |title=Post Malone To Be A Playable Character In WWE 2K24, Curates Soundtrack |url=https://www.fightful.com/wrestling/post-malone-be-playable-character-wwe-2k24-curates-soundtrack |access-date=February 26, 2024 |work=Fightful |date=February 16, 2024}}</ref>

==Personal life==
As of 2019, Malone resided in [[Cottonwood Heights, Utah]], in a multimillion-dollar {{convert|12,700|sqft|adj=on}} home.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Post Malone is the latest star to call Cottonwood Heights his home|url=https://kslnewsradio.com/1911658/post-malone-is-the-latest-star-to-call-cottonwood-heights-his-home/?|date=September 18, 2019|website=KSLNewsRadio|access-date=May 25, 2020|archive-date=May 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200528142736/https://kslnewsradio.com/1911658/post-malone-is-the-latest-star-to-call-cottonwood-heights-his-home/|url-status=live}}</ref> His former home in [[San Fernando Valley, California]], was burgled on September 1, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/09/post-malone-old-home-burglarized-armed-suspects-seeking-rapper/ |title=Post Malone's Old Home Robbed by Armed Suspects Seeking Rapper |work=XXL Mag|access-date=September 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910204613/http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/09/post-malone-old-home-burglarized-armed-suspects-seeking-rapper/|archive-date=September 10, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

On August 21, 2018, Malone boarded a plane leaving [[Teterboro Airport]] and was scheduled to land at [[Luton Airport|London Luton Airport]]. The tires blew out during takeoff and the plane was rerouted to [[Stewart International Airport]] for an emergency landing.<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=http://time.com/5373617/post-malone-plane-emergency-landing/ |title=Post Malone's Plane Makes Emergency Landing After Tires Blew Out |magazine=Time|access-date=September 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826204913/http://time.com/5373617/post-malone-plane-emergency-landing/|archive-date=August 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The plane landed safely.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://variety.com/2018/music/news/post-malone-plane-emergency-landing-1202912011/ |title=Plane Carrying Post Malone Makes Safe Emergency Landing |last=Stedman |first=Alex |date=August 21, 2018 |work=Variety|access-date=September 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909125414/https://variety.com/2018/music/news/post-malone-plane-emergency-landing-1202912011/|archive-date=September 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Once the plane had landed, Malone tweeted about the incident, writing "i landed guys. thank you for your prayers. can't believe how many people wished death on me on this website. fuck you. but not today."<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://twitter.com/PostMalone/status/1031997717634076672 |title=Beerbongs & Bentleys on Twitter |work=Twitter|access-date=September 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909125459/https://twitter.com/PostMalone/status/1031997717634076672|archive-date=September 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

Malone was involved in a car crash on September 8, 2018. Malone's white [[Rolls-Royce Wraith (2013)|Rolls-Royce Wraith]] was driving through [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica]] in the early morning when it collided with another car at 3:30 am. Although no one was severely injured in the incident, several people were treated for minor injuries.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-45458880 |title=Post Malone car crash: 'God must hate me' |date=September 8, 2018 |work=BBC News|access-date=September 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909195513/https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-45458880|archive-date=September 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Quinn |first=Dave |title=Post Malone Totals Car Two Weeks After Plane's Emergency Landing: 'God Must Hate Me' |url=https://people.com/music/post-malone-car-accident-after-plane-emergency/ |access-date=2023-06-22 |website=Peoplemag |language=en}}</ref>

Malone was in a three-year-long relationship with Ashlen Diaz, ending in November 2018.<ref name="Us Weekly" /> In May 2022, Malone announced that he was expecting his first child with his current girlfriend.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Post Malone Announces He's Expecting His First Child: 'I'm the Happiest I've Ever Been' |url=https://www.complex.com/music/post-malone-expecting-first-child-with-girlfriend |access-date=2022-05-03 |website=Complex |language=en |archive-date=May 3, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220503230354/https://www.complex.com/music/post-malone-expecting-first-child-with-girlfriend |url-status=live }}</ref> In June, during an appearance on ''[[The Howard Stern Show]]'', Malone revealed that he and his girlfriend are engaged and have welcomed a daughter, whose name has been kept private, but her initials "DDP" are tattooed on his forehead. The song "Yours" on his album ''[[F-1 Trillion]]'' is inspired by his daughter as he envisions her getting married when she is older.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Post Malone Announces Birth of Daughter – and His Engagement |url=https://www.yahoo.com/lifestyle/post-malone-announces-birth-daughter-170453529.html |access-date=2022-06-13 |website=Yahoo |date=June 13, 2022 |language=en-US |archive-date=June 13, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220613181352/https://www.yahoo.com/lifestyle/post-malone-announces-birth-daughter-170453529.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-06-13 |title=Post Malone Confirms He Welcomed a Baby Girl With His Fiancée |url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1334356/post-malone-confirms-he-welcomed-a-baby-girl-with-his-fiancee |access-date=2022-06-13 |website=E! Online |archive-date=June 13, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220613181350/https://www.eonline.com/news/1334356/post-malone-confirms-he-welcomed-a-baby-girl-with-his-fiancee |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Mason |first=Anthony |date=2024-08-11 |title=Post Malone on success, loneliness, and making his audience know they're loved - CBS News |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/post-malone-f-1-trillion/ |access-date=2024-08-14 |website=www.cbsnews.com |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Post Malone on success, acceptance, and his new country album - CBS News |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/video/post-malone-on-success-acceptance-and-his-new-country-album/ |access-date=2024-08-14 |website=www.cbsnews.com |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Galbraith |first=Alex |date=2024-08-11 |title=Post Malone Says His Daughter Saved His Life |url=https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/post-malone-says-his-daughter-saved-his-life/ |access-date=2024-08-14 |website=Us Weekly |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-08-12 |title=Post Malone reveals how baby daughter saved his life |url=https://uk.news.yahoo.com/post-malone-reveals-baby-daughter-011212323.html |access-date=2024-08-14 |website=Yahoo News |language=en-GB}}</ref>

===Health===
In March 2020, a video surfaced that showed Malone falling and behaving oddly on stage to his song, "[[I Fall Apart]]", which made fans worry about his well-being and health.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gladstoneobserver.com.au/news/disturbing-post-malone-footage-surfaces/3961907/|title='He needs help': Fears for musician Post Malone|last=Strang|first=Fay|date=March 7, 2020|website=[[The Observer]]|access-date=March 8, 2020|archive-date=August 28, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210828051335/https://www.couriermail.com.au/entertainment/music/he-needs-help-fans-worry-as-disturbing-post-malone-footage-surfaces/news-story/eb10b52d38cdabc49b90ac69d21f2704?nk=f76b4e676757baa55d28ebf3fedb2529-1630127615|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2020/03/post-malone-falls-on-stage/|title=Post Malone Falls on Stage in Nashville During 'I Fall Apart'|last=Farrel|first=Paul|date=March 6, 2020|website=[[Heavy.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307161205/https://heavy.com/entertainment/2020/03/post-malone-falls-on-stage/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> Malone later said that he was "not on drugs and I feel the best I've ever fucking felt in my life". His manager Dre London likewise claimed there was no need to worry and that Malone's behavior was part of the "act". Malone's father Richard Post also commented on the artist's behavior, stating that he does not "want to come across as dismissive to those of you who have expressed concern about Austin. Your sincerity and kindness regarding him is certainly heartwarming and appreciated."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.syracuse.com/celebrity-news/2020/03/post-malone-responds-to-concerned-fans-im-not-on-drugs.html|title=Post Malone responds to concerned fans: 'I'm not on drugs'|last=Herbert|first=Geoff|date=March 8, 2020|website=syracuse.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308190451/https://www.syracuse.com/celebrity-news/2020/03/post-malone-responds-to-concerned-fans-im-not-on-drugs.html|archive-date=March 8, 2020|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/07/entertainment/post-malone-drugs-concert-health-concern-trnd/index.html|title=Post Malone denies drug use after fans express concern for his health|last=Elassar|first=Alaa|date=March 7, 2020|website=[[CNN]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307202352/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/07/entertainment/post-malone-drugs-concert-health-concern-trnd/index.html|archive-date=March 7, 2020|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9330574/post-malone-not-on-drugs|title=Post Malone Says He Is 'Not on Drugs': 'I Feel F—king Fantastic'|last=Joyner|first=Simone|date=March 9, 2020|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url-status=live|access-date=March 9, 2020|archive-date=April 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406114629/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9330574/post-malone-not-on-drugs}}</ref>

During his 2022 interview with Howard Stern, Malone revealed he has long struggled with alcoholism, but has recovered with the help of his fiancée.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.mediaite.com/entertainment/post-malone-reveals-battle-with-alcoholism-it-got-to-a-terrible-point/amp/ |title= Post Malone Reveals Battle with Alcoholism: 'It Got to a Terrible Point' |website= [[Mediaite]] |date= 20 June 2022 |access-date= July 2, 2022 |archive-date= July 2, 2022 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20220702224934/https://www.mediaite.com/entertainment/post-malone-reveals-battle-with-alcoholism-it-got-to-a-terrible-point/amp/ |url-status= live }}</ref>

===Tattoos===
[[File:Post Malone Stavernfestivalen 2018 (203031).jpg|thumb|The tattoo under Post Malone's chin reads "STONEY", namesake of his [[Stoney (album)|debut album]].]]

Malone has a number of tattoos that he inked himself and has also inked tattoos on several friends and acquaintances.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malone-shows-the-first-tattoo-hes-ever-done-himself-news.50909.html |title=Post Malone Shows The First Tattoo He's Ever Done Himself |work=HotNewHipHop|access-date=May 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180524032340/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/post-malone-shows-the-first-tattoo-hes-ever-done-himself-news.50909.html|archive-date=May 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> As of early 2021, he has at least 78 tattoos.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.menshealth.com/entertainment/a35470817/post-malone-tattoos/|title=Yes, The True Meaning Behind Every Post Malone Tattoo|magazine=[[Men's Health]]|date=February 15, 2021|last=St. Clair|first=Josh|access-date=August 10, 2021|archive-date=August 10, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210810160816/https://www.menshealth.com/entertainment/a35470817/post-malone-tattoos/|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Political views===
Malone has a tattoo of U.S. president [[John F. Kennedy]] on his arm, and has said that Kennedy was "the only President to speak out against the crazy corruption stuff that's going on in our government nowadays."<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7632407/post-malone-jfk-assassination-trump-inauguration-breakfast-club |title=Post Malone Talks JFK Assassination & Trump Inauguration on 'The Breakfast Club' |magazine=Billboard|access-date=August 8, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818040311/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7632407/post-malone-jfk-assassination-trump-inauguration-breakfast-club|archive-date=August 18, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2016, Malone stated that if asked to perform at the [[inauguration of Donald Trump]] he would not have been opposed,<ref name="Trump">{{cite web |url=http://uproxx.com/realtalk/post-malone-trump-inauguration/ |title=Post Malone Isn't Exactly Opposed To Performing At Trump's Inauguration |date=December 20, 2016 |access-date=October 15, 2017 |publisher=Uproxx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171016122759/http://uproxx.com/realtalk/post-malone-trump-inauguration/|archive-date=October 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> though he stated that neither Trump nor [[Hillary Clinton]] were fit for [[president of the United States]] and expressed his support for [[Bernie Sanders]] during the election cycle.<ref name="Trump" />

Malone later expressed a dislike for Trump in a November 2017 interview for ''[[Rolling Stone]].'' In the same interview, he revealed that he has a large collection of guns and believes it is an American right to own and operate guns. Malone also expressed a strong interest in [[conspiracy theories]] when he said, "There's crazy shit that goes on that we can't explain."<ref name="rollingstone">{{cite magazine |last1=Weiner |first1=Jonah |title=Post Malone: Confessions of a Hip-Hop Rock Star |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/rockstar-rapper-post-malone-talks-guns-bieber-race-w511979 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |access-date=November 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171118211646/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/rockstar-rapper-post-malone-talks-guns-bieber-race-w511979|archive-date=November 18, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> During a trip to Canada in 2018, Malone was interviewed and when asked what the "biggest lie is", he replied "The biggest lie in the world is the U.S. government. It's a fucking reality show and I think there's gonna be a lot of weird shit that happens within our generation that really changes the way of the world."<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/post-malone-us-government-interview/ |title=Post Malone Says "the U.S. Government Is the Biggest Lie" |date=March 1, 2018 |work=Highsnobiety|access-date=March 1, 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200322055328/https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/post-malone-us-government-interview/|archive-date=March 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>

